00:22:01,467 --> 00:22:10,314
[SPEAKER_08]: One of the great perks of getting deeply involved in politics in your community are these intergenerational friendships that you otherwise wouldn't have had the opportunity to have.

216
00:22:11,775 --> 00:22:19,861
[SPEAKER_08]: Similar to Vice President Lazzaro, I met Len first when I went to my first Medford Democratic Caucus meeting over a decade ago.

217
00:22:20,201 --> 00:22:24,725
[SPEAKER_08]: He quickly clocked me as a new face, and at the time the youngest person there.

218
00:22:25,285 --> 00:22:28,127
[SPEAKER_08]: and he nominated me to go to the convention, which he went to as well.

219
00:22:28,947 --> 00:22:33,831
[SPEAKER_08]: We reconnected a few years later when I ran for city council, and he quickly became a fixture in my life.

220
00:22:34,931 --> 00:22:45,638
[SPEAKER_08]: Over weekly coffees, a spot on his schedule that I'm pretty sure I usurped from former councilor night, Len regaled me with seven decades of Medford political history and his insights.

221
00:22:46,199 --> 00:22:53,964
[SPEAKER_08]: He offered lots of good advice and the occasional ominous warning from some person you'd never heard of, and I would roll my eyes and he would take it in stride.

222
00:22:55,285 --> 00:23:09,340
[SPEAKER_08]: He had a genuine nonjudgmental curiosity about politics and people in the city, and he was rewarded for that with friendships of people who have been here forever, who were brand new, people who agreed with him, and people who definitely did not.

223
00:23:10,879 --> 00:23:18,942
[SPEAKER_08]: Over my political career, Len would rotate through titles for himself within my campaign, senior advisor, old hand, campaign manager.

224
00:23:19,922 --> 00:23:23,003
[SPEAKER_08]: But in retrospect, the most apt title has always been friend.

225
00:23:23,583 --> 00:23:25,824
[SPEAKER_08]: So I'm lucky to call him my friend.

